Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Mortimer was born in 1134. She married Lord William Malet in 1150, in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1213, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, Angleterre","Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Maud de Mortimer est née en 1134. Elle a épousé Lord William Malet en 1150, à Curry Mallet, Somerset, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée en 1213, à l’âge de 79 ans."},"de":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Maud de Mortimer wurde 1134 geboren. Sie hat 1150 in Curry Mallet, Somerset, England Lord William Malet geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 1213 im Alter von 79 Jahren."},"ht":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","Curry Mallet, Somerset, England":"Curry Mallet, Somerset, England","Alkborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alkborough, Lincolnshire, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"1134–1213":"1134–1213","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1213":"1213","1059":"1059","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1150":